This paper is primarily concerned with game theory, specifically the study of Nash and correlated equilibria. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory and Economics) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also deals with decision-making under uncertainty, which falls under the scope of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of geometry and polytopes suggests a connection to cs.LG (Machine Learning), while the analysis of sets and their properties relates to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the study of equilibria and their characterization may also be relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
